// sema_valid_return_slice_defer_sync.ember — the legitimate synchronous
// return_slice_defer pattern (slice-escape safety Stage 2). A fn returns its
// slice arg (borrow_slice borrows param 0 into the return), and the CALLER
// reads the result synchronously within its own frame (r[0], r[1]) — it does
// NOT return r or store r to a global. The call result is tagged localview
// (propagated via is_local_array_view's CallExpr case), but the synchronous
// reads are NOT escape sites (IndexExpr returns i64, not a slice), so no
// guard fires. Sema must accept it.
//
// This is the canonical pattern from tests/lang/runtime_language_features.ember
// (return_slice_defer), isolated as a focused sema_valid regression so the
// borrow-propagation design's headline guarantee — that the synchronous
// read-after-borrow stays valid — is pinned independently.
fn borrow_slice(s: i64[]) -> i64[] { return s; }
fn ok() -> i64 {
    let a: i64[2];
    a[0] = 41; a[1] = 42;
    let r: i64[] = borrow_slice(a[..]);
    return r[0] + r[1];
}
